<ns596:section xmlns:ns596="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.web.history.history">
         <ns597:title xmlns:ns597="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The origin of the World Wide Web</ns597:title>
         <ns598:para xmlns:ns598="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
             The current Web can be traced back to a project at <ns599:abbrev xmlns:ns599="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">CERN</ns599:abbrev> (The European 
             Organization for Particle Physics Research) in 1989 when Tim Berners-Lee and Robert Cailliau
             built <ns600:emphasis xmlns:ns600="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">ENQUIRE</ns600:emphasis> - a method of documenting which concentrates on a system
             being broken down into smaller parts, and having those parts refer to each other.
         </ns598:para>
         <ns601:para xmlns:ns601="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
             While being technically rather different than the Web we use today, the core ideas were
             the same. Much of the motivation behind this project was for Berners-Lee to be able to
             easily access library information scattered across different servers.
         </ns601:para>
         <ns602:para xmlns:ns602="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
             In november 1990, Berners-Lee published a formal proposal for the <ns603:emphasis xmlns:ns603="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">World Wide Web</ns603:emphasis>,
             and wrote the first Web Page on a NeXT workstation. A month later he built all the tools necessary
             for a functioning web, including a Web Browser (which was a Web Editor as well) and a Web Server.
         </ns602:para>
         <ns604:para xmlns:ns604="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
             Three standards were established, and it is because of these that the web has flourished to become the most
             revolutionary medium of communication in the history of mankind:
             <ns605:itemizedlist xmlns:ns605="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                 <ns606:listitem xmlns:ns606="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                     <ns607:formalpara xmlns:ns607="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                         <ns608:title xmlns:ns608="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Uniform Resource Locator (URL)</ns608:title>
                         <ns609:para xmlns:ns609="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                             specifies how each unit of information has a unique "address" at which
                             it can be found, regardless of the location of the requester.
                         </ns609:para>
                     </ns607:formalpara>                     
                 </ns606:listitem>
                 <ns610:listitem xmlns:ns610="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                     <ns611:formalpara xmlns:ns611="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                         <ns612:title xmlns:ns612="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP)</ns612:title>
                         <ns613:para xmlns:ns613="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                             specifies how browsers and servers exchange information with each other.
                         </ns613:para>
                     </ns611:formalpara>                     
                 </ns610:listitem>
                 <ns614:listitem xmlns:ns614="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                     <ns615:formalpara xmlns:ns615="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                         <ns616:title xmlns:ns616="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)</ns616:title>
                         <ns617:para xmlns:ns617="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                             specifies a method of encoding so that structured text information can be 
                             displayed on a variety of devices as <ns618:emphasis xmlns:ns618="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">pages</ns618:emphasis> or
                             <ns619:emphasis xmlns:ns619="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">documents</ns619:emphasis>.
                         </ns617:para>
                     </ns615:formalpara>                     
                 </ns614:listitem>
             </ns605:itemizedlist>
             
             <ns620:emphasis xmlns:ns620="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Hyperlinks</ns620:emphasis> (which reside in HTML pages) are the simple mechanisms
             with which pages refer to other pages in one-way relationships. The unidirectionality of
             these relationships are what made HTML prevail over previous hypertext attempts. This allows
             the linking to target pages without the target's knowledge.
         </ns604:para>
         
         
